We are provided with the following information: 1. A 75-year-old has a 50% chance of living at least another 10 years. 2. A 75-year-old has a 20% chance of living at least another 15 years. 3. An 80-year-old has a 25% chance of living at least another 10 years. To solve this, we first note the survival probabilities for a 75-year-old: - \( S(10) = 0.5 \) (probability of surviving 10 years from age 75) - \( S(15) = 0.2 \) (probability of surviving 15 years from age 75) We need to find the survival probability for an 80-year-old to live at least another 5 years, which is \( S'(5) \). We assume that the survival function for an 80-year-old can be modeled by normalizing the survival function of a 75-year-old by the survival probability to age 80. This is done by dividing the survival probabilities of the 75-year-old by the survival probability to age 80 (denoted as \( S(5) \)). First, we calculate \( S(5) \) for the 75-year-old using the given probabilities: - The probability of surviving 15 years from age 75 is \( S(15) = 0.2 \). - The probability of surviving 10 years from age 75 is \( S(10) = 0.5 \). The survival probability from age 80 to 85 (5 years) is \( S(5) \). Using the given data: - The probability of surviving 15 years from age 75 is \( S(15) = S(10) \times S(5) \). - Solving for \( S(5) \), we get \( S(5) = \frac{S(15)}{S(10)} = \frac{0.2}{0.5} = 0.4 \). Next, we use this \( S(5) \) to find the survival probability for an 80-year-old: - The probability of surviving 10 years from age 80 is given as 0.25. - This probability can be expressed as \( S'(10) = \frac{S(15)}{S(5)} \). - Solving for \( S'(5) \), we get \( S'(5) = \frac{S(10)}{S(5)} = \frac{0.5}{0.8} = 0.625 \). Thus, the probability that an 80-year-old person will live at least another 5 years is \(\boxed{\dfrac{5}{8}}\).
